caption:
â€œThe climate crisis weâ€™re facing is an opportunity for people to recognize the power of Indigenous knowledge and to recognize that tribes have the ability, if we could empower them, to help co-manage the environment up and down the state.â€â€”Kouslaa Kessler-Mata, Yak Tityu Tityu Yak TiÅ‚hini Northern Chumash and Yokut
Â 
Along Californiaâ€™s windswept coast, in the rocky crags and tide pools, California Indians (as this group prefers to be called) have subsisted for millennia on fish, abalone and seaweed, never taking more than can be naturally replaced. The effects of the climate crisis combined with unsustainable harvesting by non-native people have decimated their traditional food sources. Today, despite regulations, they continue the hard work of subsistence gathering and keep their cultural practices alive.

They saw mending as one responseâ€”an act of healing, acknowledging and honoring the labor and resources that went into making the garment. In 2016, the sisters launched The Far Woods to share mending tutorials far and wide. And, in 2020, they wrote and illustrated Mending Life: A Handbook for Repairing Clothes and Hearts.â

caption:
In 1972, Yvon Chouinard and Tom Frost opened the Chouinard Equipment catalog by urging climbers to stop using pitons, their best-selling product, in order to protect the rock. The clean climbing principles they outlined interrogated the highest ideals of climbing and instilled the values that drive Patagonia to this day. We're commemorating the 50th anniversary of the â€™72 catalog by republishing their essay in full, so that it may inspire a new generation of climbers and help renew our own commitments: to putting style over summit, to the climbing community, and to the planet weâ€™re still working to save.â 
â 
Read it through the link in bio.â 
Photo: Tom Frost

caption:
Fifty years ago, Yvon Chouinard, Tom Frost and Doug Robinson urged a new ethic for climbing that emphasized self-reliance, restraint and respect for the rock. â

caption:
In 1972, Chouinard Equipment bet the farm, urging climbers to stop using the companyâ€™s best-selling product to protect the rock. â€‹
â€‹
Clean climbingâ€”making the switch from pitons to chocksâ€”fundamentally changed both the art of the sport and the ethos of the community. It was climbingâ€™s first environmental movement and instilled the values that drive Patagonia to this day. But more importantly, it was a challengeâ€”what were climbers capable of achieving in order to protect the places they love?â€‹
â€‹
50 years later, weâ€™re asking that question again. â€‹
â€‹
Celebrating the ethic laid down in the 1972 Chouinard Equipment catalog means bringing humility, intention and creativity to every climb and inviting all climbers to build this legacy with us. Itâ€™s a commitment to the sport we love, to everything we make and to the planet weâ€™re still working to save.â€‹
â€‹
Visit the link in our bio for more.
